<br>
And then there are girls trying to act like they are.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
And then there are men trying to act like they are women <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
Gotta look out for that one, too.<br>
<br>
But on a more serious note, there does seem to be a push to try and get men to be more like women, whatever that's supposed to mean. Be more &quot;in touch with your feelings&quot;, don't be &quot;afraid to cry&quot;, etc. Don't get me wrong, being sensitive <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>to your girlfriend or wife's feelings</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is good, but being sensitive <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>in general</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> just makes you neurotic. I know it's a stereotype and all that, but I honestly think that most women want their men to have more solidarity and substance than that. You shouldn't be a cold, unemotional brick wall, but in my experience most women want to have an emotional anchor -- someone who can empathize with them but not get caught up in the turbulence himself. This really shouldn't come as a surprise to anyone, but men and women a different *gasp*! And it just wouldn't be any fun if they weren't. No, you can't rely on stereotypes, but we all exhibit them to some degree whether we'll admit it or not.<br>
<br>
Long story short, be yourself. As cheesy and hackneyed as it is, it's still solid advice. There's someone out there for everyone. Even the most socially inept and the most despicable low-life have been known to find love. When you meet him/her do you want be acting like yourself or like someone else? Lots of people wind up in long-term relationships, forced to be something they're not just to maintain it because they fear losing what they've got, even if it's not what they want. That's no way to live life. If you're perennially shy or self-concious, you'll have to try to change your <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>behavior</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> because you've got to play the game to win, but don't try to hide it or fake it. Just work around it.<br>
<br>
And, it's worth pointing out that there's nothing wrong with being single in the first place. Value what you've got now, because tomorrow... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=perifv>PeriFV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(11/25/03 1:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2136.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Can't win.  (do Norrathian women really want the truth?)</span><hr size=1> Then there's women who are more like men, personality wise. I'm a woman, and I've lost track of the men who have told me that I'm &quot;such a guy.&quot; I have a terrible time having a close friendship with other women. I just hate the games that we play even with each other. Me for male friendships. <br>
